goes here or there.

00:15:56.260 --> 00:16:00.060 align:middle line:84%
So I will do at any
given time what I--

00:16:00.060 --> 00:16:01.210 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Are doing now.

00:16:01.210 --> 00:16:02.512 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: --feel in my
heart is perhaps the way I

00:16:02.512 --> 00:16:02.970 align:middle line:90%
could serve best.

00:16:02.970 --> 00:16:05.320 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: And you are a catalyst
for change in many ways,

00:16:05.320 --> 00:16:08.010 align:middle line:84%
and this campaign is a catalyst
for change in many ways,

00:16:08.010 --> 00:16:10.122 align:middle line:84%
because you've started
the conversation.

00:16:10.122 --> 00:16:12.370 align:middle line:84%
You have the spark
that has ignited

00:16:12.370 --> 00:16:14.870 align:middle line:90%
the pink elephant in the room.

00:16:14.870 --> 00:16:19.510 align:middle line:84%
And that-- in my opinion, you've
already won by doing that,

00:16:19.510 --> 00:16:21.080 align:middle line:90%
because you really have.

00:16:21.080 --> 00:16:24.740 align:middle line:84%
In addition to that, you have
200,000 followers on Twitter

00:16:24.740 --> 00:16:28.150 align:middle line:84%
at this moment, 500,000 on
Facebook, hundreds of thousands

00:16:28.150 --> 00:16:29.320 align:middle line:90%
in the women's movement.

00:16:29.320 --> 00:16:32.150 align:middle line:84%
You have a large
momentum behind you

00:16:32.150 --> 00:16:34.445 align:middle line:84%
of supporters of people
who are expressing--

00:16:34.445 --> 00:16:35.820 align:middle line:84%
and those are just
the people who

00:16:35.820 --> 00:16:38.660 align:middle line:84%
have liked you on those
particular environments.

00:16:38.660 --> 00:16:40.670 align:middle line:84%
There's hundreds of
thousands more who haven't.

00:16:40.670 --> 00:16:43.850 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: Yes,
but in our community,

00:16:43.850 --> 00:16:46.380 align:middle line:84%
we can't rest on that,
and I'll tell you why.

00:16:46.380 --> 00:16:49.600 align:middle line:84%
Our community, the
transformational community,

00:16:49.600 --> 00:16:52.300 align:middle line:84%
has not developed the
habits of democracy.

00:16:52.300 --> 00:16:55.760 align:middle line:84%
Liking someone on
Facebook is not

00:16:55.760 --> 00:16:57.960 align:middle line:90%
a vote on primary day, June 3.

00:16:57.960 --> 00:17:00.160 align:middle line:84%
And I think that's
very important.

00:17:00.160 --> 00:17:02.325 align:middle line:84%
Just saying to me, I really
support you-- Sometimes

00:17:02.325 --> 00:17:03.950 align:middle line:84%
we say these days I
support you, and it

00:17:03.950 --> 00:17:06.960 align:middle line:84%
doesn't mean anything
other than I support you.

00:17:06.960 --> 00:17:11.052 align:middle line:84%
So that in itself will
not win this election.

00:17:11.052 --> 00:17:12.510 align:middle line:10%
Winning this election
means to make

00:17:12.510 --> 00:17:14.930 align:middle line:10%
sure you're registered to
vote on June 3, to talk

00:17:14.930 --> 00:17:17.869 align:middle line:10%
to your friends, to go to
marianneforcongress.com,

00:17:17.869 --> 00:17:20.050 align:middle line:10%
to look at all the
events we have going on,

00:17:20.050 --> 00:17:23.540 align:middle line:10%
the public town halls,
the meetings on GMOs, food

00:17:23.540 --> 00:17:26.220 align:middle line:10%
and health with John Robbins,
coming to the Thursday night.

00:17:26.220 --> 00:17:30.630 align:middle line:84%
Every Thursday night we do a
volunteer meeting-- 305 Rose

00:17:30.630 --> 00:17:33.450 align:middle line:84%
Avenue in Venice--
and people showing up,

00:17:33.450 --> 00:17:34.880 align:middle line:84%
being part of the
field operation,

00:17:34.880 --> 00:17:37.160 align:middle line:84%
going, talking to people
in different neighborhoods.

00:17:37.160 --> 00:17:40.770 align:middle line:84%
So liking something on
Facebook is absolutely not,

00:17:40.770 --> 00:17:43.020 align:middle line:84%
and I think that's an important
tweak of consciousness

00:17:43.020 --> 00:17:43.580 align:middle line:90%
right there.

00:17:43.580 --> 00:17:44.000 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Thank you.

00:17:44.000 --> 00:17:46.041 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: Sending
out email lists, you know,

00:17:46.041 --> 00:17:49.830 align:middle line:84%
we've talked to people and my
colleagues asking, will you?

00:17:49.830 --> 00:17:51.870 align:middle line:84%
Reid Tracy did the
most beautiful letter--

00:17:51.870 --> 00:17:56.720 align:middle line:84%
it meant so much to me-- on
the Hay House newsletter,

00:17:56.720 --> 00:17:58.920 align:middle line:84%
and Wayne Dyer on
his newsletter.

00:17:58.920 --> 00:18:00.080 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Great.

00:18:00.080 --> 00:18:01.729 align:middle line:90%
>> WILLIAMSON: That's really--

00:18:01.729 --> 00:18:02.520 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Influence.

00:18:02.520 --> 00:18:03.811 align:middle line:90%
>> WILLIAMSON: --I support you.

00:18:03.811 --> 00:18:07.380 align:middle line:84%
Yes, and what does that actually
mean in terms of action?

00:18:07.380 --> 00:18:10.350 align:middle line:84%
That's what would create it
happening, if it happens.

00:18:10.350 --> 00:18:13.180 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: So let me ask you
about being a woman and running

00:18:13.180 --> 00:18:14.130 align:middle line:90%
in this candidacy.

00:18:14.130 --> 00:18:14.450 align:middle line:90%
>> WILLIAMSON: Yes.

00:18:14.450 --> 00:18:17.100 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: And you have held
some great conferences on women

00:18:17.100 --> 00:18:19.490 align:middle line:84%
in politics, and you've always
been a really big advocate

00:18:19.490 --> 00:18:20.350 align:middle line:90%
for it.

00:18:20.350 --> 00:18:24.490 align:middle line:84%
What would you do in the
event you were treated--

00:18:24.490 --> 00:18:26.110 align:middle line:84%
and you got the
congressional seat

00:18:26.110 --> 00:18:28.880 align:middle line:84%
and you were discriminated
against by other Congress

00:18:28.880 --> 00:18:31.041 align:middle line:90%
members as a woman in Congress?

00:18:31.041 --> 00:18:33.540 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: Well, even though
there are not nearly enough

00:18:33.540 --> 00:18:37.010 align:middle line:84%
women in Congress, only
20%, I don't think--

00:18:37.010 --> 00:18:40.300 align:middle line:84%
I have not heard any of them
say that they feel discriminated

00:18:40.300 --> 00:18:42.300 align:middle line:90%
against as women.

00:18:42.300 --> 00:18:44.180 align:middle line:84%
You know, if you look
at the statistics,

00:18:44.180 --> 00:18:47.540 align:middle line:84%
if a woman is running for
political office against a man,

00:18:47.540 --> 00:18:50.240 align:middle line:84%
she wins as often
as the man does

00:18:50.240 --> 00:18:51.886 align:middle line:90%
because there are women voters.

00:18:51.886 --> 00:18:53.260 align:middle line:84%
The place where
there's a problem

00:18:53.260 --> 00:18:55.130 align:middle line:84%
is that not enough
women are running.

00:18:55.130 --> 00:18:58.370 align:middle line:84%
So, you know, Lisa, for me,
the feminist conversation today

00:18:58.370 --> 00:19:01.490 align:middle line:84%
is not about, oh, I'm
not getting enough of.

00:19:01.490 --> 00:19:03.790 align:middle line:84%
We need to be, as American
women now, talking about

00:19:03.790 --> 00:19:06.550 align:middle line:84%
how to wield the
power that we do have.

00:19:06.550 --> 00:19:08.830 align:middle line:84%
That's what our conversation
as women needs to be.

00:19:08.830 --> 00:19:11.801 align:middle line:90%


00:19:11.801 --> 00:19:12.300 align:middle line:90%
Right?

00:19:12.300 --> 00:19:13.571 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: That went
right through my heart.

00:19:13.571 --> 00:19:14.413 align:middle line:90%
>> WILLIAMSON: Good, baby, good.

00:19:14.413 --> 00:19:15.255 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Yes, ma'am.

00:19:15.255 --> 00:19:16.390 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON:
That's why I'm here.

00:19:16.390 --> 00:19:17.723 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Right through my heart.

00:19:17.723 --> 00:19:19.190 align:middle line:90%
Yes, absolutely.

00:19:19.190 --> 00:19:21.810 align:middle line:84%
So in addition to
that conversation,

00:19:21.810 --> 00:19:24.520 align:middle line:84%
let's talk about any
type of scrutiny.

00:19:24.520 --> 00:19:27.010 align:middle line:84%
Of course you're going to
get bad news, good news, all

00:19:27.010 --> 00:19:27.564 align:middle line:90%
of that.

00:19:27.564 --> 00:19:28.980 align:middle line:84%
What are your
feelings about that?

00:19:28.980 --> 00:19:30.770 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON:
It's embarrassing,

00:19:30.770 --> 00:19:35.030 align:middle line:84%
but when somebody does a bad
picture of you or something--

00:19:35.030 --> 00:19:37.870 align:middle line:84%
and the press that
I've seen so far--

00:19:37.870 --> 00:19:39.710 align:middle line:84%
there was one the other
day that was snarky.

00:19:39.710 --> 00:19:41.168 align:middle line:84%
I don't know if
you've heard, Lisa.

00:19:41.168 --> 00:19:43.910 align:middle line:84%
I'm just a New Age guru,
lightweight, woo-woo thinker.

00:19:43.910 --> 00:19:47.450 align:middle line:90%


00:19:47.450 --> 00:19:50.520 align:middle line:84%
I think that enough
time has gone by now,

00:19:50.520 --> 00:19:53.070 align:middle line:84%
and the transformational
wisdom is

00:19:53.070 --> 00:19:56.280 align:middle line:84%
sort of baked into the cake
of our public discourse

00:19:56.280 --> 00:19:59.705 align:middle line:84%
so that now I think people
see through the ruse of that.

00:19:59.705 --> 00:20:02.190 align:middle line:84%
New Age guru is
just kind of used

00:20:02.190 --> 00:20:06.450 align:middle line:84%
as a label to trivialize and
peripheralize and minimize

00:20:06.450 --> 00:20:07.290 align:middle line:90%
your conversation.

00:20:07.290 --> 00:20:07.720 align:middle line:90%
I'm sure you get--

00:20:07.720 --> 00:20:08.010 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Categorize.

00:20:08.010 --> 00:20:08.890 align:middle line:90%
>> WILLIAMSON: --some of that.

00:20:08.890 --> 00:20:10.960 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: I did read that
you've never worn a silk scarf

00:20:10.960 --> 00:20:11.420 align:middle line:90%
in your life.

00:20:11.420 --> 00:20:12.294 align:middle line:90%
>> WILLIAMSON: Yeah.

00:20:12.294 --> 00:20:12.797 align:middle line:90%
Cut velvet.

00:20:12.797 --> 00:20:13.630 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Cut velvet.

00:20:13.630 --> 00:20:14.320 align:middle line:90%
>> WILLIAMSON: Silk I have.

00:20:14.320 --> 00:20:14.903 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Silk.

00:20:14.903 --> 00:20:16.774 align:middle line:90%
>> WILLIAMSON: But cut velvet.

00:20:16.774 --> 00:20:17.690 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: That's great.

00:20:17.690 --> 00:20:19.630 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: This is where we
need to stand up for each other

00:20:19.630 --> 00:20:20.125 align:middle line:90%
too.

00:20:20.125 --> 00:20:20.460 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Yeah.

00:20:20.460 --> 00:20:22.626 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: And there's
nothing like other people

00:20:22.626 --> 00:20:23.550 align:middle line:90%
having your back.

00:20:23.550 --> 00:20:25.960 align:middle line:84%
The other day there was
some article that came out--

00:20:25.960 --> 00:20:27.700 align:middle line:84%
and this is something
else people need

00:20:27.700 --> 00:20:30.520 align:middle line:84%
to know-- so an article
came out on a blog.

00:20:30.520 --> 00:20:31.920 align:middle line:90%
Or maybe it wasn't a blog.

00:20:31.920 --> 00:20:33.295 align:middle line:84%
I think it was a
major newspaper,

00:20:33.295 --> 00:20:34.560 align:middle line:90%
but it was the online version.

00:20:34.560 --> 00:20:39.970 align:middle line:84%
And so many times journalists
are so irresponsible these days

00:20:39.970 --> 00:20:42.355 align:middle line:84%
that they just repeat
something or say

00:20:42.355 --> 00:20:44.620 align:middle line:90%
something that's not even true.

00:20:44.620 --> 00:20:46.680 align:middle line:84%
So somebody said
something, and that's not

00:20:46.680 --> 00:20:48.450 align:middle line:90%
what I had said at all.

00:20:48.450 --> 00:20:50.100 align:middle line:90%
That's when it's very painful.

00:20:50.100 --> 00:20:52.720 align:middle line:84%
Because I've read articles
about myself where I've thought,

00:20:52.720 --> 00:20:56.480 align:middle line:84%
if I was reading this, I
wouldn't like me either.

00:20:56.480 --> 00:20:59.740 align:middle line:84%
So it's very painful when
you're caricatured as someone

00:20:59.740 --> 00:21:01.060 align:middle line:90%
that you know you're not.

00:21:01.060 --> 00:21:03.560 align:middle line:84%
But what was significant
about this incident

00:21:03.560 --> 00:21:06.130 align:middle line:84%
was that they said
what they said,

00:21:06.130 --> 00:21:08.580 align:middle line:84%
it was a total lie,
and then a gentleman

00:21:08.580 --> 00:21:11.210 align:middle line:84%
that I know wrote
in immediately.

00:21:11.210 --> 00:21:13.280 align:middle line:84%
How dare you call
yourself a journalist?

00:21:13.280 --> 00:21:15.110 align:middle line:84%
This is what she said,
not what you said.

00:21:15.110 --> 00:21:18.040 align:middle line:84%
She actually said this, and
here's the source, the article.

00:21:18.040 --> 00:21:20.710 align:middle line:84%
You said she had this many of
this, but that's actually not.

00:21:20.710 --> 00:21:21.900 align:middle line:90%
Here's the source.

00:21:21.900 --> 00:21:23.400 align:middle line:90%
And he just laid into it.

00:21:23.400 --> 00:21:26.800 align:middle line:84%
And they changed it
immediately and apologized.

00:21:26.800 --> 00:21:29.810 align:middle line:84%
And I think too many
people don't realize that.

00:21:29.810 --> 00:21:33.060 align:middle line:84%
For instance, if somebody
something said to me about me

00:21:33.060 --> 00:21:34.770 align:middle line:84%
that you know is
untrue and then there's

00:21:34.770 --> 00:21:37.859 align:middle line:84%
a comment to the newspaper
from Lisa Garr, no kidding.

00:21:37.859 --> 00:21:38.400 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Yes.

00:21:38.400 --> 00:21:40.420 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: And that's
what's really beautiful.

00:21:40.420 --> 00:21:41.370 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: That's the power
of influence, though.

00:21:41.370 --> 00:21:43.370 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: Not when
lies are said about you,

00:21:43.370 --> 00:21:45.630 align:middle line:84%
but when everybody even
who knows better is quiet.

00:21:45.630 --> 00:21:47.967 align:middle line:84%
And I think we're all
learning about that now.

00:21:47.967 --> 00:21:50.300 align:middle line:84%
That's what it means when
people say I've got your back.

00:21:50.300 --> 00:21:51.190 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Very important.

00:21:51.190 --> 00:21:52.090 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: We've got
to have each other's back,

00:21:52.090 --> 00:21:52.990 align:middle line:90%
particularly as women.

00:21:52.990 --> 00:21:53.320 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Yeah.

00:21:53.320 --> 00:21:53.840 align:middle line:90%
All right.

00:21:53.840 --> 00:21:55.381 align:middle line:84%
Let's talk about
some of your agendas

00:21:55.381 --> 00:21:58.465 align:middle line:84%
on what you're planning on going
forward with if you're elected.

00:21:58.465 --> 00:21:59.215 align:middle line:90%
>> WILLIAMSON: OK.

00:21:59.215 --> 00:21:59.550 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: OK.

00:21:59.550 --> 00:22:01.091 align:middle line:84%
So we've got a couple
of issues here.

00:22:01.091 --> 00:22:02.907 align:middle line:84%
We've got overturning
the Citizens United?

00:22:02.907 --> 00:22:05.240 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: Well, you can't
really overturn-- I mean,

00:22:05.240 --> 00:22:07.700 align:middle line:84%
the only thing that could
overturn it is if we had

00:22:07.700 --> 00:22:11.591 align:middle line:84%
a different Supreme Court and
there was actually a repeal

00:22:11.591 --> 00:22:12.090 align:middle line:90%
of it.

00:22:12.090 --> 00:22:16.144 align:middle line:84%
That's nothing that's in
the-- No congressperson gets

00:22:16.144 --> 00:22:17.060 align:middle line:90%
to make that decision.

00:22:17.060 --> 00:22:20.580 align:middle line:84%
But what, as a congressperson,
I can do, in addition to

00:22:20.580 --> 00:22:23.370 align:middle line:84%
co-sponsoring this bill
that Nancy Pelosi introduced

00:22:23.370 --> 00:22:25.780 align:middle line:84%
the other day, which
is very exciting,

00:22:25.780 --> 00:22:28.290 align:middle line:84%
called By the People bill,
I think it's called, which

00:22:28.290 --> 00:22:31.960 align:middle line:84%
does take a step forward,
but I want to help magnify

00:22:31.960 --> 00:22:35.100 align:middle line:84%
the message and the conversation
in Congress about starting

00:22:35.100 --> 00:22:36.970 align:middle line:84%
a constitutional
amendment, passing

00:22:36.970 --> 00:22:39.840 align:middle line:84%
a constitutional amendment
which will outlaw

00:22:39.840 --> 00:22:43.600 align:middle line:84%
the undo influence of money and
establish that corporations do

00:22:43.600 --> 00:22:45.410 align:middle line:84%
not have the rights
of personhood.

00:22:45.410 --> 00:22:47.460 align:middle line:84%
That's what I would
make my primary,

00:22:47.460 --> 00:22:49.010 align:middle line:84%
because that's the
underlying issue.

00:22:49.010 --> 00:22:49.450 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: That's
what you start with.

00:22:49.450 --> 00:22:49.530 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:22:49.530 --> 00:22:50.660 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: Then we can
talk about child poverty,

00:22:50.660 --> 00:22:53.310 align:middle line:84%
which is the second highest
in all the advanced world.

00:22:53.310 --> 00:22:55.690 align:middle line:84%
We can talk about
mass incarceration,

00:22:55.690 --> 00:22:57.780 align:middle line:90%
which is highest in the world.

00:22:57.780 --> 00:23:01.200 align:middle line:84%
We can talk about so many
issues, the GMOs, the military,

00:23:01.200 --> 00:23:03.757 align:middle line:84%
so many things, but there's
an underlying cancer.

00:23:03.757 --> 00:23:06.090 align:middle line:84%
There's an underlying issue
underlying all those issues,

00:23:06.090 --> 00:23:07.980 align:middle line:84%
and that's the
influence of money.

00:23:07.980 --> 00:23:09.570 align:middle line:90%
So anything related to that--

00:23:09.570 --> 00:23:10.610 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: That does
actually have to do with--

00:23:10.610 --> 00:23:11.210 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: --that's
where I go first.

00:23:11.210 --> 00:23:14.000 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: So just to rein
in the food companies,

00:23:14.000 --> 00:23:17.010 align:middle line:84%
like with the GMOs and so forth,
it goes back to the corporate

00:23:17.010 --> 00:23:17.720 align:middle line:90%
interests, right?

00:23:17.720 --> 00:23:18.510 align:middle line:90%
>> WILLIAMSON: Right, exactly.

00:23:18.510 --> 00:23:19.160 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: Goes back
to that issue.

00:23:19.160 --> 00:23:19.220 align:middle line:90%
>> WILLIAMSON: Exactly.

00:23:19.220 --> 00:23:21.970 align:middle line:84%
As long as they can spend
that many millions of dollars.

00:23:21.970 --> 00:23:23.740 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: What about halting
the extension of the Keystone

00:23:23.740 --> 00:23:24.220 align:middle line:90%
Pipeline?

00:23:24.220 --> 00:23:24.761 align:middle line:90%
Explain that.

00:23:24.761 --> 00:23:27.220 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: Oh, it's
just tragic, isn't it?

00:23:27.220 --> 00:23:30.590 align:middle line:84%
So the government comes out
with a report the other day,

00:23:30.590 --> 00:23:35.180 align:middle line:84%
basically giving the president
a pass, if he chooses it.

00:23:35.180 --> 00:23:37.779 align:middle line:84%
It all feels like theater
right now, doesn't it?

00:23:37.779 --> 00:23:39.820 align:middle line:84%
Because now we say, oh,
well, a government report

00:23:39.820 --> 00:23:41.650 align:middle line:84%
came out and said
it wouldn't really

00:23:41.650 --> 00:23:44.170 align:middle line:84%
contribute to carbon--
of course it will.

00:23:44.170 --> 00:23:45.300 align:middle line:90%
We all know that it will.

00:23:45.300 --> 00:23:47.060 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: Explain what
the Keystone Pipeline is.

00:23:47.060 --> 00:23:49.060 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: The Keystone
Pipeline, of course,

00:23:49.060 --> 00:23:52.310 align:middle line:84%
is the one that's going to send
all the oil from Canada from

00:23:52.310 --> 00:23:53.080 align:middle line:90%
the tar sands.

00:23:53.080 --> 00:23:54.650 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: This is the
fracking conversation?

00:23:54.650 --> 00:23:55.840 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: No, that's
not a fracking conversation.

00:23:55.840 --> 00:23:56.040 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Oh, it's different?

00:23:56.040 --> 00:23:56.280 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:23:56.280 --> 00:23:57.710 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: No, it is
different than the fracking

00:23:57.710 --> 00:23:58.690 align:middle line:90%
conversation.

00:23:58.690 --> 00:24:01.730 align:middle line:84%
And it absolutely increases
the carbon footprint,

00:24:01.730 --> 00:24:05.600 align:middle line:84%
and the president had said
that he would not allow it

00:24:05.600 --> 00:24:11.730 align:middle line:84%
if it was proven by a government
report that it would increase.

00:24:11.730 --> 00:24:14.554 align:middle line:84%
And the report
basically says, well,

00:24:14.554 --> 00:24:15.970 align:middle line:84%
if they don't send
it by pipeline,

00:24:15.970 --> 00:24:17.344 align:middle line:84%
they're going to
send it by train

00:24:17.344 --> 00:24:19.550 align:middle line:84%
anyway, which is not
necessarily true.

00:24:19.550 --> 00:24:22.710 align:middle line:84%
So I think that those of us
who feel strongly about this,

00:24:22.710 --> 00:24:25.250 align:middle line:84%
at some point we've got
to just hold the line.

00:24:25.250 --> 00:24:30.590 align:middle line:84%
This issue of climate
change and the relationship

00:24:30.590 --> 00:24:32.860 align:middle line:84%
between the carbon and
the climate change,

00:24:32.860 --> 00:24:35.890 align:middle line:84%
this is a clear and present
danger at this point.

00:24:35.890 --> 00:24:39.140 align:middle line:90%
This is not even a debate.

00:24:39.140 --> 00:24:42.130 align:middle line:84%
We have an Energy and Commerce
Committee that wouldn't even

00:24:42.130 --> 00:24:44.920 align:middle line:84%
allow for hearings with
scientists talking.

00:24:44.920 --> 00:24:48.290 align:middle line:84%
And Congressman Waxman, who is
there now, has been a champion.

00:24:48.290 --> 00:24:48.990 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Yes.

00:24:48.990 --> 00:24:49.960 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: He said,
let's have hearings.

00:24:49.960 --> 00:24:51.730 align:middle line:90%
Let's have scientists talk.

00:24:51.730 --> 00:24:57.150 align:middle line:84%
And they would not allow it
because the Republicans who

00:24:57.150 --> 00:24:59.090 align:middle line:84%
are in control
would not allow it.

00:24:59.090 --> 00:25:00.584 align:middle line:84%
The American people
must speak up,

00:25:00.584 --> 00:25:02.250 align:middle line:84%
and the American
people are speaking up.

00:25:02.250 --> 00:25:02.640 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Yes.

00:25:02.640 --> 00:25:04.390 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: But I,
as a congressperson,

00:25:04.390 --> 00:25:06.000 align:middle line:90%
would contribute to that voice.

00:25:06.000 --> 00:25:11.210 align:middle line:84%
Because we are the
only species that

00:25:11.210 --> 00:25:12.960 align:middle line:90%
is destroying our own habitat.

00:25:12.960 --> 00:25:15.600 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: Well, this is a very
important time in history

00:25:15.600 --> 00:25:17.440 align:middle line:84%
for you to be running
for that reason.

00:25:17.440 --> 00:25:17.940 align:middle line:90%
>> WILLIAMSON: Thank you.

00:25:17.940 --> 00:25:20.560 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: Because there's such
an awareness now and a need.

00:25:20.560 --> 00:25:21.910 align:middle line:90%
And this is a global movement.

00:25:21.910 --> 00:25:22.660 align:middle line:90%
This is not just--

00:25:22.660 --> 00:25:22.950 align:middle line:90%
>> WILLIAMSON: Absolutely.

00:25:22.950 --> 00:25:24.250 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: --limited
to the United States.

00:25:24.250 --> 00:25:25.416 align:middle line:90%
And that's the beauty of it.

00:25:25.416 --> 00:25:27.405 align:middle line:84%
There's two million
environmental organizations

00:25:27.405 --> 00:25:28.530 align:middle line:90%
now.

00:25:28.530 --> 00:25:31.780 align:middle line:84%
If you could gather those
together and mobilize those,

00:25:31.780 --> 00:25:34.280 align:middle line:84%
then you've made a huge impact,
and you've started the ball.

00:25:34.280 --> 00:25:36.900 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: Well, there are
so many of these organizations,

00:25:36.900 --> 00:25:40.180 align:middle line:84%
but there's a limit to what
we can do from the sidelines.

00:25:40.180 --> 00:25:42.300 align:middle line:84%
And, you know, at a
certain point, you say,

00:25:42.300 --> 00:25:44.790 align:middle line:84%
I'm tired of just trying
to lobby my congressperson.

00:25:44.790 --> 00:25:47.678 align:middle line:90%
I think I just want their seat.

00:25:47.678 --> 00:25:50.235 align:middle line:84%
We need to start
running candidacies.

00:25:50.235 --> 00:25:52.610 align:middle line:84%
We always think of ourselves
as trying to influence them.

00:25:52.610 --> 00:25:54.610 align:middle line:90%
No, we need to become them.

00:25:54.610 --> 00:25:55.755 align:middle line:90%
That's what I figured out.

00:25:55.755 --> 00:25:56.630 align:middle line:90%
That was my epiphany.

00:25:56.630 --> 00:25:59.180 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: You were
just done, right?

00:25:59.180 --> 00:26:01.420 align:middle line:90%
>> WILLIAMSON: Just move over.

00:26:01.420 --> 00:26:02.890 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: Let me
ask you a question.

00:26:02.890 --> 00:26:04.540 align:middle line:84%
You have been
responsible for starting

00:26:04.540 --> 00:26:06.880 align:middle line:84%
major organizations,
the Project Angel Food,

00:26:06.880 --> 00:26:08.529 align:middle line:90%
the Center for the Living.

00:26:08.529 --> 00:26:09.320 align:middle line:90%
>> WILLIAMSON: Yes.

00:26:09.320 --> 00:26:10.770 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: OK.

00:26:10.770 --> 00:26:13.770 align:middle line:84%
In your beginning of
those organizations,

00:26:13.770 --> 00:26:16.810 align:middle line:84%
did you learn anything that
you would carry forward now

00:26:16.810 --> 00:26:18.680 align:middle line:84%
to running your
campaign, something

00:26:18.680 --> 00:26:21.160 align:middle line:84%
you would do differently or
you wouldn't do differently?

00:26:21.160 --> 00:26:22.650 align:middle line:90%
What have you carried forward?

00:26:22.650 --> 00:26:25.108 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: Well, I think
every experience I've ever had

00:26:25.108 --> 00:26:26.090 align:middle line:90%
in my life has--

00:26:26.090 --> 00:26:27.090 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Applies to now?

00:26:27.090 --> 00:26:28.506 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON:
--taught me things,

00:26:28.506 --> 00:26:33.140 align:middle line:84%
information to
move forward with.

00:26:33.140 --> 00:26:35.340 align:middle line:84%
I like to think
I've just matured

00:26:35.340 --> 00:26:40.190 align:middle line:84%
as a person beyond
who I was when

00:26:40.190 --> 00:26:44.860 align:middle line:84%
I started an organization
20 years ago.

00:26:44.860 --> 00:26:49.460 align:middle line:84%
So yes, starting
organizations, like running

00:26:49.460 --> 00:26:53.970 align:middle line:84%
political campaigns,
it's not an easy thing.

00:26:53.970 --> 00:26:59.550 align:middle line:84%
And who you are as a person is
as important as what you do.

00:26:59.550 --> 00:27:02.200 align:middle line:90%


00:27:02.200 --> 00:27:06.110 align:middle line:84%
I think there are a lot
of things I have learned,

00:27:06.110 --> 00:27:08.985 align:middle line:84%
but most of them have to
do with my own orientation.

00:27:08.985 --> 00:27:13.263 align:middle line:90%


00:27:13.263 --> 00:27:15.060 align:middle line:84%
You know, sometimes
you want work

00:27:15.060 --> 00:27:20.100 align:middle line:84%
to get done so badly
that you forget

00:27:20.100 --> 00:27:27.870 align:middle line:84%
that the human relationships
within the work are the work.

00:27:27.870 --> 00:27:28.990 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Wow.

00:27:28.990 --> 00:27:30.490 align:middle line:90%
Very well said.

00:27:30.490 --> 00:27:32.200 align:middle line:84%
And what you're
talking about now

00:27:32.200 --> 00:27:35.150 align:middle line:84%
is exactly how every
American feels.

00:27:35.150 --> 00:27:36.890 align:middle line:84%
If you fix what's
going on in here,

00:27:36.890 --> 00:27:38.350 align:middle line:90%
then you can fix it out there.

00:27:38.350 --> 00:27:42.792 align:middle line:84%
But until you have seen it and
addressed it, it doesn't work.

00:27:42.792 --> 00:27:44.750 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: Everything
we do is infused with

00:27:44.750 --> 00:27:46.940 align:middle line:84%
the consciousness
with which we do it.

00:27:46.940 --> 00:27:50.630 align:middle line:84%
So we have to take care
of our state of being,

00:27:50.630 --> 00:27:54.470 align:middle line:84%
out of which emerges the
most powerful state of doing.

00:27:54.470 --> 00:27:59.740 align:middle line:84%
Many people have
undervalued, underestimated,

00:27:59.740 --> 00:28:03.620 align:middle line:84%
and under-efforted
in the area of being.

00:28:03.620 --> 00:28:06.100 align:middle line:84%
But in our crowd, if
we're not careful,

00:28:06.100 --> 00:28:09.450 align:middle line:84%
we're going to underestimate,
undervalue, and under-effort

00:28:09.450 --> 00:28:11.210 align:middle line:90%
the area of doing.

00:28:11.210 --> 00:28:14.630 align:middle line:84%
And the issue is the being and
then the doing and the being

00:28:14.630 --> 00:28:15.620 align:middle line:90%
and then the doing.

00:28:15.620 --> 00:28:19.400 align:middle line:84%
I once saw some graffiti that
said, to do is to be, Hegel.

00:28:19.400 --> 00:28:21.890 align:middle line:84%
The other one said, to
be is to do, Sartre.

00:28:21.890 --> 00:28:24.530 align:middle line:84%
And then it said do be,
do be, do, Frank Sinatra.

00:28:24.530 --> 00:28:25.655 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: I like that, yeah.

00:28:25.655 --> 00:28:26.380 align:middle line:90%
Frank Sinatra.

00:28:26.380 --> 00:28:27.100 align:middle line:90%
I like that one.

00:28:27.100 --> 00:28:29.038 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: So stupid, but
I always get a laugh out of it.

00:28:29.038 --> 00:28:29.976 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: I know.

00:28:29.976 --> 00:28:32.590 align:middle line:84%
I actually have the
magnet on my refrigerator.

00:28:32.590 --> 00:28:33.090 align:middle line:90%
OK.

00:28:33.090 --> 00:28:35.210 align:middle line:84%
So you have this
incredible energy,

00:28:35.210 --> 00:28:38.020 align:middle line:84%
and you seem completely
comfortable with where

00:28:38.020 --> 00:28:39.120 align:middle line:90%
you're going with this.

00:28:39.120 --> 00:28:40.620 align:middle line:84%
Is there anything
else that you want

00:28:40.620 --> 00:28:43.750 align:middle line:84%
to leave us with and tell us
in terms of your campaign?

00:28:43.750 --> 00:28:46.350 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: What I want
to leave you with, Lisa,

00:28:46.350 --> 00:28:51.310 align:middle line:84%
is how much it matters that
you've had me on your program,

00:28:51.310 --> 00:28:53.930 align:middle line:84%
how much it matters that I
have felt psychologically

00:28:53.930 --> 00:28:57.140 align:middle line:84%
and emotionally so
supported by you,

00:28:57.140 --> 00:29:03.910 align:middle line:84%
and this is how things
happen, one person showing up

00:29:03.910 --> 00:29:07.482 align:middle line:84%
at a time, and that you
have made your support--

00:29:07.482 --> 00:29:09.690 align:middle line:84%
I have never felt from you,
oh, I really support you.

00:29:09.690 --> 00:29:10.560 align:middle line:90%
I hope you win.

00:29:10.560 --> 00:29:12.360 align:middle line:84%
I have felt, I
really support you.

00:29:12.360 --> 00:29:13.403 align:middle line:90%
Come be on my show.

00:29:13.403 --> 00:29:13.986 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Yeah.

00:29:13.986 --> 00:29:14.350 align:middle line:90%
Yeah.

00:29:14.350 --> 00:29:16.391 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: I really
support you this or that.

00:29:16.391 --> 00:29:20.590 align:middle line:84%
And you, in that sense,
demonstrate, not only for me

00:29:20.590 --> 00:29:24.600 align:middle line:84%
but for everyone,
what it looks like.

00:29:24.600 --> 00:29:26.020 align:middle line:90%
So I thank you very, very much.

00:29:26.020 --> 00:29:29.310 align:middle line:84%
That would be my main message
is of gratitude to you and to so

00:29:29.310 --> 00:29:32.740 align:middle line:84%
many like you who are
really inspiring me.

00:29:32.740 --> 00:29:36.070 align:middle line:84%
And I feel such gratitude as
I go through this process.

00:29:36.070 --> 00:29:36.930 align:middle line:90%
I can't tell you.

00:29:36.930 --> 00:29:40.020 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: The quote that you
said about not being afraid

00:29:40.020 --> 00:29:43.440 align:middle line:84%
of the light that you
are shining within,

00:29:43.440 --> 00:29:46.500 align:middle line:84%
I see you shining that
light so strongly,

00:29:46.500 --> 00:29:50.219 align:middle line:84%
and you don't seem that you're
afraid of your own light.

00:29:50.219 --> 00:29:51.302 align:middle line:90%
>>WILLIAMSON: I think we--

00:29:51.302 --> 00:29:54.170 align:middle line:90%


00:29:54.170 --> 00:29:56.770 align:middle line:84%
People talk about how
living in the light is hard.

00:29:56.770 --> 00:29:59.260 align:middle line:84%
No, living outside
the light is hard.

00:29:59.260 --> 00:30:02.710 align:middle line:84%
People talk about how
the light is scary.

00:30:02.710 --> 00:30:07.010 align:middle line:84%
Well, actually, the darkness
is what should scare us.

00:30:07.010 --> 00:30:09.970 align:middle line:10%
Really going for it,
people say, is scary,

00:30:09.970 --> 00:30:13.080 align:middle line:10%
but I think not going
for it is more scary.

00:30:13.080 --> 00:30:14.307 align:middle line:90%
It eats you up inside.

00:30:14.307 --> 00:30:14.890 align:middle line:90%
>> LISA: Yeah.

00:30:14.890 --> 00:30:18.920 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: We all know
too much now that we can live

00:30:18.920 --> 00:30:22.140 align:middle line:84%
comfortably and peacefully
within ourselves not doing what

00:30:22.140 --> 00:30:25.990 align:middle line:84%
we can to, in
whatever small way,

00:30:25.990 --> 00:30:28.599 align:middle line:84%
create the world that we know
in our hearts is possible.

00:30:28.599 --> 00:30:30.890 align:middle line:84%
>> LISA: You're such an
inspiration to no longer settle

00:30:30.890 --> 00:30:34.460 align:middle line:84%
for that and no longer be quiet
about that and to really take

00:30:34.460 --> 00:30:34.990 align:middle line:90%
a stand.

00:30:34.990 --> 00:30:36.330 align:middle line:84%
If you can do it,
we can all do it.

00:30:36.330 --> 00:30:37.690 align:middle line:90%
So thank you so much, Marianne.

00:30:37.690 --> 00:30:38.440 align:middle line:84%
>> WILLIAMSON: Right
back at you, Lisa.

00:30:38.440 --> 00:30:39.860 align:middle line:90%
Thank you so much, darling.

